The '''1970-71 season''' was [[France|French]] [[association football|football]] club [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]]'s 1st season of existence and their 1st season in the second-tier of [[Football in France|French football]], the [[Ligue 2|Division 2]]. Paris Saint-Germain was managed by [[Pierre Phelipon]], who replaced symbolic Stade Saint-Germain coach [[Roger Quenolle]] and became the club's first ever coach. The club was chaired by Pierre-Ãtienne Guyot until Guy CrÃ©scent took over. Paris Saint-Germain was present in the [[1970â71 French Division 2|1970â71 Division 2]] and the [[1970â71 Coupe de France]].<ref name="coach">{{cite news 
| title = PSG Coaches from 1970 to 1979
| url = http://www.psg.fr/en/Club/6020001/Entraineurs/38681/p1
| work = PSG.fr
| accessdate = 28 July 2010}}</ref> Paris Saint-Germain played some home matches at the [[Stade Jean-Bouin]]. The attendance was lower than in the Stade Georges LefÃ¨vre and the club chose to play in Saint-Germain. The Stade Georges LefÃ¨vre of the [[Camp des Loges]] was, from 1970 to 1974, the main stadium of the club. Paris Saint-Germain's average home gate for the 1970-71 season was 3,019. The club's first logo and hymn appeared. Allez Paris! became the first official anthem of the club and was performed by [[Annie Cordy]].<ref name="s70">{{cite news 
| title = Saison 1970/71
| url = http://psg70.free.fr/accueil.htm
| work = PSG70
| accessdate = 25 May 2010}}</ref> Pierre-Ãtienne Guyot assigned a clear goal for the team and Pierre Phelipon. He had pretty big ambitions for the new capital club and declared that Paris Saint-Germain started the season with the prospect of gaining promotion to French football's top-flight, the [[Ligue 1|Division 1]].<ref name="s70"/> 

==News==
During the 1968-69 season the Saint-Germain based club, reached the quarter finals of the  [[Coupe de France 1968-69|French Cup]], where they faced eventual champions, [[Olympique de Marseille]]. The first leg took place at the [[Parc des Princes]] and the second leg at the [[Stade VÃ©lodrome]]. The match saw the logic triumph of l'OM (2-0 and 5-1). It was an encounter that had driven the Parisian public out of hiding, as they played amid a crowd of just over 14,500 spectators. The following year brought even more success as the club finished third in the CFA, thus gaining promotion to the second division. But all this success couldn't mar the fact that [[Paris]], the capital city of France, didn't have a renowned team. Teams from other major cities had successful and historically prestigious clubs, such as [[FC Nantes|Nantes]], [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]], [[AS Saint-Ãtienne|Saint-Ãtienne]], and Marseille. The lack of Parisian based teams were apparent to see, mainly in fact between the two world wars, famous clubs like [[Club FranÃ§ais]], [[Olympique de Paris]], [[CA Paris-Charenton|CA Paris]], all had disappeared from the French footballing spectrum. Only [[Red Star Saint-Ouen|Red Star]], remained in the first division, and they were marooned at the bottom of the table, and the only other Parisian teams of note was the second division outfits, Paris-Jonville and Paris-Neuilly - but even they were more obscure with no real ambitions or means to gain a decent fan base or reputation.<ref>{{cite news 
| title = Paris St-Germain: The Who, What, Where and How?
| url = http://www.bigsoccer.com/forum/showthread.php?t=181703
| work = [[BigSoccer]]
| date = 25 March 2005
| accessdate = 28 July 2010}}</ref> 

It was in 1970, that a bigger club was to be formed for Paris. On 1 February 1970, radio host and personality [[Pierre Bellemare]] announced a call looking subscriptions for the creation of a great club in [[Paris]] through radio broadcaster [[Europe 1]]. More than 20,000 subscribers, desperate to see an elite football club in the capital, responded to the offer and, a group of local businessmen, led by Guy CrÃ©scent, CEO of Calberson and Pierre-Ãtienne Guyot, Vice-president of [[RCF Paris]], asked the directors of Stade Sangermanois to become part of their project. On 20 May, following the orders of the [[French Football Federation]], the Stade Saint-Germain of Henri Patrelle and [[Paris FC]] merged, giving birth to Paris Saint-Germain Football Club. The FFF attempted to revive top level football in Paris. The following day, the merging was adopted unanimously at a meeting of Paris FC members. On 30 May, the FFF published the list of the clubs that would participate in next year's [[Ligue 2|Division 2]] championship. Paris Saint-Germain F.C. appeared, replacing the Stade Saint-Germain, on the list for promotion.<ref>''France Football'', NÂ°1261 du 2 juin 1970, p.3. Liste des clubs qualifiÃ©s pour la D2 1970-71 annoncÃ©e le 30 mai au Conseil fÃ©dÃ©ral de la FFF</ref> On 10 June 1970, the merging protocol was signed, officializing the fusion. On 17 June, the merger between the Stade Saint-Germain and the Association "Paris Football Club" was formalized. Paris Saint-Germain was born. President Guy CrÃ©scent adopted the "socios" system, the same of the [[Spain|Spanish]] clubs. The supporters financially contributed in the club gaining voice in the decisions taken by the management. 18,000 shareholders represented by delegates joined the club, a new initiative which unfortunately will last only two years in [[France]]. On 26 June, the Stade Saint-Germain headquarters, located in the Municipality of [[Saint-Germain-en-Laye]], were transferred to the seventeenth arrondissement of Paris at the 183 avenue de Clichy. That same day, the extraordinary general meeting of the club ended with the assignment of the trio that would manage the club. Pierre-Ãtienne Guyot was named President and two Vice-presidents were assigned: Guy CrÃ©scent as Administrative Director and Henri Patrelle as Sporting Director.<ref name="s70"/>

Days later, [[Pierre Phelipon]] became the first ever coach of PSG in 1970, replacing the symbolic Stade Sangermanois coach, [[Roger Quenolle]]. The [[Saint-Germain-en-Laye]] based first team, who had just earned promotion to the [[Ligue 2|Division 2]], allowed the brand new Paris Saint-Germain to start its career in France's second tier. The club benefited from the large fan-base and a squad full of good players as a result of the merger. The squad was mainly constituted by Stade Saint-Germain players. Phelipon alternated his job as coach and player to help out make a competitive team consisting of both amateur and professional players.<ref name="coach"/> After Pierre's appointment as coach, [[Jean Djorkaeff]], captain of the [[France national football team|French national football team]], joined Paris Saint-Germain from [[Olympique de Marseille]] in June 1970. Djorkaeff joined [[Jean-Pierre Destrumelle]], with whom he played at Marseille a year before. ''Tchouki'' was the first licensed professional player of the club. On 28 July 1970, Jean Djorkaeff and the rest of PSG's squad completed their first training session at the [[Camp des Loges]]. All of the new club officers assisted to witness this unique event: President Pierre-Ãtienne Guyot, who barely recovered from a serious operation, along Vice-presidents Guy CrÃ©scent and Henri Patrelle, were accompanied by the General Assembly of the club. Coach Pierre Phelipon explained the outcome of this meeting: ''"The most important thing for me is to hasten the adaptation of the amateurs with professionals. There is always some latent rivalry. But I am convinced that within a few days, everything will be definitively resolved. They must not fall out with each other and stand together."'' Guy CrÃ©scent solemnly declared to the players: ''"Now you belong to a family. Paris Football Club and Saint-Germain, are over. Now we are the PSG!"'' <ref>{{cite news 
| title = Une date historique
| url = http://www.psg.fr/fr/Article/003001/Article/49618/Une-date-historique
| work = PSG.fr
| date = 28 July 2010
| accessdate = 28 July 2010}}</ref> 

Paris Saint-Germain F.C. was officially founded on 12 August 1970 after the positions of the Administration Council were equitably shared between Parisians and Sangermanois by vote. On 27 August, the Official Journal confirmed the creation of Paris Saint Germain Football Club. For several years, this date was seen as the foundation date. The creation of Paris Saint-Germain marked the reappearance of a major club in Paris after the decline of [[RCF Paris|Racing Paris]], Red Star, and [[Stade franÃ§ais (football)|Stade FranÃ§ais]]. Thanks to the financial support of Paris FC's structure, PSG could reinforce the squad. Although the club maintained its amateur status, Paris Saint-Germain took advantage of a new regulation which allowed the signing of six professional players. The club strengthen the squad with the signings of [[Roland Mitoraj]] from Saint-Ãtienne, French goalkeeper Patrice Py, Daniel Guicci, Zivco Lukic, goalscorer [[Jean-Claude Bras]] from [[Belgium|Belgian]] outfit [[R.F.C. de LiÃ¨ge]], and Jacques RÃ©mond from [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]]. After the insistence of the "Portuguese Association of Paris", PSG agreed to recruit [[Fernando Cruz]], [[Portugal|Portuguese]] international of [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] with an impressive record. The rest of the squad was constituted of amateur players.<ref>''Paris Saint-Germain'', NÂ°1 de septembre 1971, p.17-19, prÃ©sentation de l'effectif 1971-72.</ref> On the other hand, AndrÃ© Pietrantoni left the club and joined Saint-Cyr. On 4 June 1971, Pierre-Ãtienne Guyot left the Presidency and was named President of Honour of Paris Saint-Germain. Guy CrÃ©scent became President while Henri Patrelle continued as Vice-president.<ref name="s70"/>

