==Kit==
The Stade Saint-Germain club played mainly in white until 1970, when they merged with [[Paris FC]] and adopted the red and blue colors of [[Paris]] combined with the white of [[Saint-Germain-en-Laye]]. [[Le Coq Sportif]] became Paris Saint-Germain's first official equipment provider and manufactured the [[Kit (association football)|kits]] for the club throughout the season. The first strip design of the fledgling Paris Saint-Germain in 1970 was mainly solid red. The collar and ends of the sleeves were blue and white. The club badge was on the left of the shirt and the logo of the equipment supplier, Le Coq Sportif, was generally not displayed. The shorts were white, while the socks were mainly blue with a white and red trim. The away kit was a predominantly white shirt decorated with two fine red and blue vertical bands. The shorts and socks were white. The club badge was on the left of the shirt and Le Coq Sportif had their logo on the top-right of the shirt in navy.<ref>''Les guides de [[L'Ãquipe]], Football 1969'', p.129</ref><ref>''Paris Saint-Germain'', NÂ°2 de fÃ©vrier 1971, photo officielle de l'effectif, p.16</ref>
